Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Antigua and Barbuda. The authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus. See local measures below for more details.
On 26 March the government of Antigua and Barbuda announced that from 27 March, VC Bird International Airport will be closed to international arrivals from North America and all countries of Europe on commercial flights, initially for two weeks. Flights from these regions will be allowed to arrive empty of passengers but with crew in order to repatriate foreign nationals. See Return to the UK section for more information.
On 24 March the government of Antigua and Barbuda announced with immediate effect the consolidation of its maritime border on the island of Antigua. All international maritime arrivals must enter via Nevis Street Pier in St John’s. On 26 March the government of Antigua and Barbuda announced that with immediate effect, until further notice, any non-Antigua and Barbuda national with a travel history in Canada, China, any country in Europe, Iran, South Korea, Japan, Singapore, and the USA within 28 days will not be permitted entry into Antigua and Barbuda.
Yachts are not permitted to enter Antigua and Barbuda, regardless of which country they have arrived from, and regardless of the nationality or residential status of those on board. Travellers arriving from Montserrat are being screened, which may result in extended travel time.
On 24 March the Barbuda Council announced that from 27 March all ports of entry on the island of Barbuda will be closed for 14 days.
Local Measures
On 31 March the government of Antigua and Barbuda announced that the state of emergency which began on 25 March would last until 23 May. On 8 April the government of Antigua and Barbuda announced that the complete lockdown from 2 April is extended until 06:00 on 16 April.
There are certain exemptions for those providing or seeking emergency support and supplies.
No more than two people may travel in a motor vehicle at any one time.
All people out on essential business must wear a masks that covers the nose and mouth, including when in motor vehicles.
People under the age of 18 may only leave their homes if they are accompanied by a parent or legal guardian.
All non-essential services such as bars, nightclubs, and restaurants are closed and all social gatherings are prohibited.
Essential services such as food shops and pharmacies are operating with reduced opening hours.
Public-facing government offices are also restricting opening hours and visitors.
Failure to comply with the state of emergency regulations will result in either a fine of XCD5000 or six months imprisonment.
The Antigua and Barbuda Emergency Medical Service are asking the public to call the COVID-19 inquiries hotline on 462 6843 if they suspect they might have contracted the virus, been exposed to or any other matters relating to the virus. The public are asked to call the hotline and not visit a healthcare facility unless instructed to.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
